******
[2]
Date: Tue 1 Dec 2015
Source: The Daily Telegraph [edited]
http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/newslocal/west/whooping-cough-outbreak-hits-mt-druitt-with-cases-up-450-per-cent-on-last-year/story-fngr8i5s-1227629543503


Parents are being warned to be on the lookout for symptoms of the potentially life-threatening whooping cough, as Blacktown Mt Druitt Hospital has recorded an increase of more than 450 per cent since this time in 2014.

More than 1200 cases of whooping cough were reported across western Sydney during 2015, with 200 cases reported in October 2015 alone. In 2014, only 400 cases were reported. This October 2015, more than 95 cases were reported in the Blacktown local government area, compared with just 21 cases in October 2014.

Western Sydney Local Health District Communicable diseases manager Dr Shopna Bag said cases of whooping cough had been consistently increasing. "Western Sydney Local Health District has experienced a steady increase in pertussis (whooping cough) notifications since late 2014."

Regular immunization is recommended to prevent whooping cough, with all children receiving immunisation in high school; however, immunity fades over time, and booster shots are often needed for adults.

Dr Bag said the increase in cases in western Sydney could be put down to lack of immunization. "Immunity [from] the whooping cough vaccination fades over time," Dr Bag said. After 3 or 4 years, there are enough people in the community with low levels of immunity to allow an outbreak to occur."

Pertussis is particularly dangerous for newborn babies, who may not show symptoms of a cough but may stop breathing and turn blue. To combat this risk to newborns, the NSW Government introduced the Antenatal Pertussis Vaccination program in April 2015. The program offers free vaccinations for all pregnant women in their 3rd trimester to protect children before they are born.

[Byline: Jillian McKee]

